\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}

\begin{document}

The momentum carried by each photon is given by \(\frac{h\nu}{c}\). If it is incident normally on a black surface, it exerts an impulse of \(\frac{h\nu}{c}\). The total pressure exerted would be 

\[
\frac{1}{c} \sum h\nu
\]

where the summation extends over photons of all frequencies incident on the surface per unit area per second. If \(W\) is the power of the source, then at distance \(r\), the intensity \(I\) is given by

\[
I = \frac{W}{4\pi r^2}
\]

Then the pressure \(P\) is

\[
P = \frac{I}{c} = \frac{W}{4\pi r^2 c}
\]

Substituting the given values, we have

\[
P = \frac{1000}{(4\pi)(22)(3 \times 10^8)} = 6.63 \times 10^{-8} \, \text{Pa}
\]

\end{document}
