```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{graphicx}

\begin{document}

Suppose a ray going from $A$ to $B$ traverses distances $s_1, s_2, s_3, \ldots, s_p$ in media of indices $n_1, n_2, n_3, \ldots, n_p$, respectively. The total time of flight is then (Fig. 15.15):

\begin{equation}
t = \sum_{i=1}^{p} \frac{s_i}{\nu_i} = \frac{1}{c} \sum_{i=1}^{p} n_i s_i
\end{equation}

The last summation is known as the optical path length (O.P.L). Fermat’s principle states that a ray of light traverses from one point to another by a route which takes the least time. A more stringent formulation of Fermat’s principle is as follows: A ray of light, in traversing from one point to another, regardless of the media, adopts such a route which corresponds to a stationary value of the optical path length:

\begin{equation}
\text{O.P.L} = \int_{A}^{B} n(s) \, ds
\end{equation}

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{figure15_15.png} % Placeholder for Fig. 15.15
\end{center}

A function $f(x)$ is said to have a stationary value at $x = x_0$, if its derivative $\frac{df}{dx}$ vanishes at $x = x_0$. A stationary value could correspond to a maximum or minimum. Let a ray of light proceed from $A(0, y_1)$ in a medium of index $n_1$ and be incident at $C(x, 0)$ on the interface, get refracted, and reach $B(x_2, y_2)$ in the medium of index $n_2$:

\begin{equation}
\text{O.P.L.} = n_1(AC) + n_2(CB) = n_1 \sqrt{x^2 + y_1^2} + n_2 \sqrt{(x_2 - x)^2 + y_2^2}
\end{equation}

Taking the derivative with respect to $x$ and setting it to zero for stationary value:

\begin{equation}
\frac{d(\text{O.P.L.})}{dx} = 0 \quad \Rightarrow \quad n_1 \frac{x}{\sqrt{x^2 + y_1^2}} - n_2 \frac{x_2 - x}{\sqrt{(x_2 - x)^2 + y_2^2}} = 0
\end{equation}

This simplifies to:

\begin{equation}
n_1 \sin i - n_2 \sin r = 0 \quad \Rightarrow \quad \frac{\sin i}{\sin r} = \frac{n_2}{n_1} \quad (\text{Snell's law})
\end{equation}

\end{document}
```

