\usepackage{graphicx}

\begin{document}

\section*{Mirage: An Optical Illusion}

A mirage is a type of illusion formed by light rays coming from the low region of the sky in front of the observer. On a sunny day, a road gets heated, and a temperature gradient is established in the vertical direction with the upper air layer being slightly less warm, and the corresponding indices of refraction being slightly larger. As the rays penetrate the atmospheric depth, they start bending due to refraction, becoming horizontal to the road and then bending upwards. The blue of the sky in the background produces a virtual image of a water pool, and the turbulence of air close to the road enhances the effect of a water pool with waves on the surface. This phenomenon is known as a mirage.

\subsection*{(a) Explanation with Reference to Figure}

% Include the figure here
\begin{figure}[h]
