\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}
\usepackage{graphicx}

\begin{document}

\section*{Refraction through a Sphere}

Let a ray \( PA \) enter the sphere at \( A \), refract at \( A \) and \( B \), and intersect the axis at \( F \) (see Fig. 15.23). Let \(\phi\) be the angle of incidence and \(\theta\) the angle of refraction at \( A \):

\begin{equation}
    \sin \phi = \mu \sin \theta \quad \text{(Snell's law)}
\end{equation}

For small angles, we have:

\begin{equation}
    \phi = \mu \theta
\end{equation}

In \(\triangle \Delta 1 BFC\), we apply the sine rule:

\begin{equation}
    \frac{FC}{BC} = \frac{\sin \widehat{FBC}}{\sin \widehat{BFC}} = \frac{\sin(\pi - \phi)}{\sin 2(\phi - \theta)} = \frac{\sin \phi}{\sin 2(\phi - \theta)} = \frac{\phi}{2(\phi - \theta)}
\end{equation}

since the angles are small. Hence, the equivalent focal length \( F_{\text{eq}} = FC \) is given by:

\begin{equation}
    F_{\text{eq}} = \frac{BC \cdot \phi}{2(\phi - \theta)} = \frac{\mu r}{2(\mu - 1)}
\end{equation}

where we have used equations (2), (3), and (4).

\begin{center}
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{Fig15_23.png}
    \captionof{figure}{Refraction through a sphere}
\end{center}

\end{document}
