The symbols used are: object distance $x_0$, object size $y_0$, image distance $x_i$, image size $y_i$, and radius of curvature $r$. The object-image equation can be written as:

\begin{equation}
    n_1 \left(-\frac{1}{x_0}\right) + n_2 \left(\frac{1}{x_i}\right) = \frac{n_2 - n_1}{r}
\end{equation}

The convention results in a negative value for the object distance. Paraxial rays are considered so that $\alpha_1$ and $\alpha_2$ are small. Each ray is given a height and an angle, as shown in Fig. 15.25. The distance $\epsilon$ on the axis, called sagitta, is nearly zero. Considering counterclockwise angles as positive and clockwise angles as negative, equation (1) becomes:

\begin{equation}
    n_1 \alpha_1 l_1 + n_2 (-\alpha_2 l_2) = \frac{n_2 - n_1}{r}
\end{equation}

As $l_2 = l_1$, two simultaneous equations can be written in the variables $\alpha_j$ and $l_j$ ($j = 1, 2$):

\begin{equation}
    l_2 = l_1
\end{equation}

\begin{figure}[h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{fig15_25.png}
    \caption{Passage of a light ray $P_1$ in medium of refractive index $n_1$ into medium of refractive index $n_2$ onto $P_2$.}
