At any point \( P \) on the screen at a distance \( y \) from the axis, the phase difference due to the waves coming from \( S_1 \) and \( S_2 \) will be due to the optical path difference \((S_2P - S_1P)\), as shown in Fig. 15.11:

\begin{equation}
    \delta = \frac{2\pi}{\lambda} (S_2P - S_1P)
\end{equation}

If \((S_2P - S_1P) = n\lambda\) where \( n = 0, 1, 2, \ldots \), the phase difference \(\delta = 2n\pi\), and the intensity is maximum at \( P \):

If \((S_2P - S_1P) = \left(m + \frac{1}{2}\right) \lambda\), where \( m = 0, 1, 2, \ldots \), the phase difference \(\delta = (2m + 1)\pi\) and the intensity will be zero at \( P \).

With reference to Fig. 15.11,

\begin{align}
    (S_2P)^2 &= L^2 + \left(x + \frac{d}{2}\right)^2 \\
    (S_1P)^2 &= L^2 + \left(x - \frac{d}{2}\right)^2
\end{align}

Thus,

\begin{align}
    (S_2P)^2 - (S_1P)^2 &= (S_2P + S_1P)(S_2P - S_1P) = 2xd
\end{align}

In practice, \( d \) is quite small, typically 0.5 mm, compared to \( L \), typically 1.0 m, and \( P \) is close to the axis, \( y \ll L \), so that \( S_1P \) as well as \( S_2P \) are only slightly greater than \( L \). We can then set \( S_2P + S_1P = 2L \). Therefore,

\begin{equation}
    S_2P - S_1P = \frac{2xd}{2L} = \frac{xd}{L}
\end{equation}

Therefore, the condition for maximum intensity at \( P \) is

\begin{equation}
    \frac{xd}{L} = m\lambda \quad \text{(bright fringes)}
\end{equation}

and the condition for zero intensity at \( P \) is

\begin{equation}
    \frac{xd}{L} = \left(m + \frac{1}{2}\right)\lambda \quad \text{(dark fringes)}
\end{equation}

\( m \) is called the order of the fringe system. On the axis, at \( y = 0 \), \( m = 0 \) and we have the intensity maximum. The central bright band on the screen is flanked on either side by a series of bright and dark bands corresponding to \( m = 1, 2, 3, \ldots \), the \( m \)-th bright fringe being at a distance \( y_m \) from the axis:

\begin{equation}
    y_m = \frac{m\lambda L}{d}
\end{equation}

and the \((m+1)\)-th bright fringe being at a distance

\begin{equation}
    y_{m+1} = \frac{(m+1)\lambda L}{d}
\end{equation}

The separation of the fringes \(\beta\), called the bandwidth, is given by

\begin{equation}
    \Delta y = y_{m+1} - y_m = \beta = \frac{\lambda L}{d}
\end{equation}

\[
\beta = \frac{\lambda L}{d} = \frac{612 \times 10^{-9} \times 4}{2 \times 10^{-3}} = 1.124 \times 10^{-3} \, \text{m} = 1.124 \, \text{mm}
\]

