\section*{Physics Problem Solution}

The condition for constructive interference in a single-slit diffraction pattern is given by:

\begin{equation}
a \sin \theta = m \lambda
\end{equation}

For the first minimum ($m=1$), we have:

\begin{equation}
\sin \theta = \frac{\lambda}{a}
\end{equation}

Given that $a = 1 \times \lambda = \lambda$, we can write:

\begin{equation}
a = \lambda
\end{equation}

If $D$ is the distance from the slit to the screen and $x$ is the distance of the first minimum from the central maximum, then for small angles:

\begin{equation}
\tan \theta \approx \sin \theta = \frac{x}{D}
\end{equation}

Combining equations (2) and (3), we have:

\begin{equation}
\lambda = \frac{ax}{D}
\end{equation}

Substituting the given values:

\begin{equation}
\lambda = \frac{0.02 \times 0.5}{200} = 5 \times 10^{-5} \, \text{cm} = 5000 \, \text{\AA}
\end{equation}

\end{document}
