\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}

\begin{document}

\section*{Problem}

(a) Let \( m \) be the order of interference. If the slit width \( a \) is maintained constant and the separation of the slits \( d \) is varied, the scale of the interference pattern varies, but that of the diffraction pattern remains unchanged. If the diffraction angle corresponds to the minimum given by equation (1), then a particular order of interference maxima may be absent. This is called a missing order. Thus, a missing order is realized for an angle \( \theta \) for which the following two equations are simultaneously satisfied:

\begin{equation}
d \sin \theta = m \lambda \quad (m = 1, 2, 3, \ldots)
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
a \sin \theta = n \lambda \quad (n = 1, 2, 3, \ldots)
\end{equation}

Dividing equation (1) by equation (2), we have:

\begin{equation}
\frac{d}{a} = \frac{m}{n}
\end{equation}

Since \( m \) and \( n \) are both integers, missing orders will occur when \( d/a \) is in the ratio of two integers. Expressing \( d \) as the sum of the slit width \( a \) and the opaque space \( b \) between consecutive slits, that is:

\begin{equation}
d = a + b
\end{equation}

Equation (3) can be rewritten as:

\begin{equation}
\frac{a + b}{a} = \frac{m}{n}
\end{equation}

In particular, if \( \frac{a+b}{a} = 1 \), then \( b = 0 \). In this case, the first-order spectrum will be absent, and the resultant diffraction pattern will be similar to that of a single slit. If \( \frac{a+b}{a} = 2 \), then \( a = b \), that is, the width of the slit is equal to the width of the opaque space. Here, the second-order spectrum will be absent.

(b) Given:

\[
\frac{a+b}{a} = \frac{0.16+0.8}{0.16} = 6 = \frac{m}{n}
\]

The above relation is satisfied for \( n = 1, 2, 3, \ldots \) and \( m = 6, 12, 18, \ldots \). Thus, the orders 6, 12, 18, etc., of the interference maxima will be missing in the diffraction pattern.

\end{document}
```

