\usepackage{graphicx}

\begin{document}

In Fig.~15.34, the grating space is denoted as \( AD = d \). In the triangle \(\triangle ABD\), \( \angle BAD = i \), which is the angle of incidence. Also, \( \angle DAC = \theta \), which is the angle of diffraction. In \(\triangle ABD\), the path difference between the incident rays \( YD \) and \( XA \) is given by \( BD = d \sin i \).

\begin{figure}[h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{fig15_34}
    \caption{Diffraction by a grating for a parallel beam of light which is obliquely incident.}
    \label{fig:diffraction_grating}
\end{figure}

Similarly, the path difference between the diffracted rays is \( DC = d \sin \theta \). The total path difference is:

\begin{equation}
    BD + DC = d(\sin i + \sin \theta) \tag{1}
\end{equation}

For the \( m \)-th primary maximum, we have:

\begin{equation}
    d(\sin \theta_m + \sin i) = m\lambda \tag{2}
\end{equation}

or

\begin{equation}
    \sin\left(\frac{\theta_m + i}{2}\right) = \frac{m\lambda}{2d \cos\left(\frac{\theta_m - i}{2}\right)} \tag{3}
\end{equation}

The angle of deviation of the diffracted beam is:

\begin{equation}
    \delta_m = \theta_m + i \tag{4}
\end{equation}

For \(\delta_m\) to be minimum, \(\cos\left(\frac{\theta_m - i}{2}\right)\) must be maximum, that is:

\begin{equation}
    \frac{\theta_m - i}{2} = 0 \Rightarrow \theta_m = i \tag{5}
\end{equation}

Then \(\delta_m\) will be minimum, say \( D_m \), and is given by:

\begin{equation}
    D_m = \theta_m + i = 2i \quad \text{or} \quad i = \frac{D_m}{2} \tag{6}
\end{equation}

Substituting (5) and (6) into (3):

\begin{equation}
    2d \sin\left(\frac{D_m}{2}\right) = m\lambda \tag{7}
\end{equation}

The number of lines per centimeter \( N \) is given by:

\begin{equation}
    N = \frac{1}{d} = \frac{2 \sin(20/2)}{1 \times 4.358 \times 10^{-5}} = 7969 \text{ lines/cm}
\end{equation}

\end{document}
```

